                  <lb></lb>master in Portland-street. I left my stable about one o'clock on the 19th of Febru<lb></lb>ary—I was coming back, and met the prisoner with this set of harness on his back—it had been removed out of the stable—I thought a neighbour in Wardour-street had borrowed them, and I watched the prisoner to see whether he took them there, but he passed by—I then inquired at the shop, and pursued the prisoner—I overtook him in Rath bone-place—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184103010173"></xptr>
               <p>put my hand on his shoulder, and asked him who lent him that—he said, "Mr. Somebody"—I took him back to the stable—I found a policeman, who took the prisoner—the stable-door was not locked, but the hasp I was on.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I was under the gateway—a man who looked like a coachman came and told me to take it to Mr. Jones, in the New, and he would give me 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I was going, and the witness stopped me.</p>
